m":"West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","St Katherines Chapel St Marys, Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Townshend","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Norfolk): variant of   Townsend  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Townsend","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived at the extremity of a village, from Middle English <i>toun(es)ende</i>. Compare   Town  . There may have been some confusion with   Townson  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roger Townshend was born in 1385, in West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas De Townshend, was 25 and his mother, Agnes Alice Payne, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Eleanor Giggs. He died on 16 February 1466, in his hometown, at the age of 81."},"et":{"1385–16 February 1466":"1385–16. veebruar 1466","1385–1466":"1385–1466","1390–1435":"1390–1435","1385–1440":"1385–1440","